d":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Mix<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"> in this order<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">:<\/span><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Water to <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">9 \u03bcL<\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\"><\/span><\/div><br\/><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"5BB356A00CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":25,"title":"concentration","source":{"concentration":5,"unit":"Picomolar (pM)","title":"oligonucleotide"}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"687442F00CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1.5,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"10\u00d7 T4 polynucleotide kinase buffer"}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"7830E3100CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":4,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1.5,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"100\u00a0mM DTT"}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"9A7D67900CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":5,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":1,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"T4 polynucleotide kinase"}},{"id":1054729,"guid":"A4BA68200CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":6,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":5,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":"[\u03b3-32P] ATP 3000\u00a0Ci\/mmol 185\u00a0MBq\/mL"}},{"id":1054730,"guid":"CFDEE127E11943EBB47B6F73B8D1D613","order_id":7,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>The amount of oligonucleotide is important. The molarity of most radionucleotides is very low (this can be calculated for any source as the activity\/mmol and the activity\/unit volume are provided\u2014for the recommended [\u03b3-<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">32<\/span><span>P] ATP, the molarity is 1.67 pM\/\u03bcL on the activity date). Aim to have less oligonucleotide than [\u03b3-<\/span><span style = \"vertical-align:super;\">32<\/span><span>P] ATP\u2014increasing the amount of oligo will seem to improve the incorporation, but will increase the amount of unlabeled oligonucleotide that competes for hybridization much more. In other words, this protocol produces a small amount of very highly labelled probe which is best for hybridization.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":6,"title":"Mix","icon":"MixIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059275,"guid":"B9DBE59B9DFA4C4BADD194F4DA0F4177","previous_id":1059274,"previous_guid":"130D6FDA199142B6A320454363DD63E4","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"CE7ABDE7D3C1484CB987B100D1687FCA","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"5E102748E87D4C6DAB890B2AC22F0BBE","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Incubate <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><br\/><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"D0FEA6D00CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":3600,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"D5B48DC00CF611EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":37,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"4204034CD56542A5A87B80FB9D2ED75B","order_id":4,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">In our hands 2\u00a0h or more of labeling is fine.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":1,"title":"Incubation","icon":"IncubationIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":3600},{"id":1059276,"guid":"628E123580B147DF8E5C9CC3E2FBC956","previous_id":1059275,"previous_guid":"B9DBE59B9DFA4C4BADD194F4DA0F4177","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"06B398D93A7743859FAC4E93BDA79011","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"FFECC237FD38415C9DD8CB4C3575B143","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Clean the probe through a column as for an RNA probe (as detailed in the following substeps), but use a mini Quick Spin Oligo column as oligonucleotides are retained in normal mini Quick spin columns. Incorporation can be variable.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059277,"guid":"629384F8A43548B69DDC47789E784956","previous_id":1059276,"previous_guid":"628E123580B147DF8E5C9CC3E2FBC956","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"F331BDF50A9349DA8A3FDCBC266B9DD9","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"7CD0BA8267714B8CBAF80D84B7D470E9","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Flick a mini Quick Spin column inverted and then correct way up to get the sepharose to the bottom, remove top then bottom cap (see product instructions).<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059278,"guid":"551A5B3C4A5840B58267257A8472F2F5","previous_id":1059277,"previous_guid":"629384F8A43548B69DDC47789E784956","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"03D4C090E1E24E25BB8ED96760957291","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"CD37268B540B4897A5EB1CA1A4622275","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Place the column in a 2\u00a0mL microcentrifuge tube, spin at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">, discard tube and place the column in a new 1.5\u00a0mL screw cap tube.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"6BB6A7400CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":30,"title":"centrifuge","source":{"centrifuge":"1000","duration":30,"guid":"6BB6A7400CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","id":0,"label":"","pause":null,"preset":[],"start":null,"temperature":"","temperatureUnit":10,"unit":34}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":2,"title":"Centrifugation","icon":"CentrifugationIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059279,"guid":"C8F3C2F76F0845A5B7AC6891A6E8FA0E","previous_id":1059278,"previous_guid":"551A5B3C4A5840B58267257A8472F2F5","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"B8DAFB350CA14D1EBBC481D7DA6BFC45","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"DD9C8733661D41CC9377ABAEF27C6233","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Dilute the probe with water to <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> and then pipette carefully on to the centre of the sepharose matrix in the column.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"600F8F600CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":50,"unit":"\u00b5l","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":3,"title":"Pipetting","icon":"PipettingIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059280,"guid":"DD229C430B2F48469F032D3CF0505283","previous_id":1059279,"previous_guid":"C8F3C2F76F0845A5B7AC6891A6E8FA0E","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"ACBFBD909B61489483C91EC9739BBE58","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"CD687BB665384C528E41C4FA8E7E905D","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Centrifuge at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"4C4110800CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":30,"title":"centrifuge","source":{"centrifuge":"1000","duration":240,"guid":"4C4110800CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","id":0,"label":"","pause":null,"preset":[],"start":null,"temperature":"","temperatureUnit":10,"unit":34}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":2,"title":"Centrifugation","icon":"CentrifugationIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059281,"guid":"E8969E4BFCD4476B929A9226E2371B5D","previous_id":1059280,"previous_guid":"DD229C430B2F48469F032D3CF0505283","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"8F5C0747BA944401894F72CCA6B390AF","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"08E3E485F36B4C2CB29FC42A0E5ED6D2","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Test incorporation by briefly holding the probe and column at equal distances from the Geiger counter. Use tweezers for this. At least 50% of the label should be incorporated, which means the Geiger counter will read the same signal from both column and probe. Discard the column to the radioactive waste.<\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059282,"guid":"5BC9B32522934C8791F5F60B3C80DC39","previous_id":1059281,"previous_guid":"E8969E4BFCD4476B929A9226E2371B5D","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"544540A47AF44B4B91CECCC9C752BB62","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"0E8F79E7116347ABB87F1BCEA38106C5","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Add the probe to the hybridization bottle while vertical so that it falls directly into the hybridization buffer and incubate <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"87EACEA00CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":0,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"90E2F3200CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":42,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":1,"title":"Incubation","icon":"IncubationIcon"},{"id":40,"title":"Overnight Step","icon":"Overnight"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059283,"guid":"47E31E15BAB94E36BF81919FCC8E0390","previous_id":1059282,"previous_guid":"5BC9B32522934C8791F5F60B3C80DC39","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"74BC15130BCB4BAB96E925B2406D428E","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"96083EE076B64816AABD5C73BB56E78A","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Pour the probe into a 50\u00a0mL tube (Falcon\/Corning type) and store at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"997B44600CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":-20,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"D1FF12D46EBF4305BCA198BE65F23C32","order_id":3,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">RNA probes and oligonucleotide probes can be reused up to 2 times (a total use of 3 times) but only over a week or two taking into account the half-life of the isotope. To reuse a probe, prehybridize the membrane with half the normal quantity of hybridization buffer, meanwhile defrost the probe by letting the tube stand in a beaker of hot water for 20\u00a0min then pour the probe into the hybridization bottle.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":[{"id":13,"title":"Pause point","icon":"PauseIcon"}],"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059284,"guid":"45F26FDB0CB44852B0ACB5E0165028FD","previous_id":1059283,"previous_guid":"47E31E15BAB94E36BF81919FCC8E0390","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"E2314557175F4C1FA63497B5718DE7D6","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"168D6B3EB8994E16A530F487B9D2D9CB","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">See\u00a0Section \"Hybridization of RNA Probes\"\u00a0for washing and exposing directions: <\/div><\/div>"}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":0},{"id":1059285,"guid":"63EFC4766DEB4EC7BDDB32E9DD5D3DF7","previous_id":1059284,"previous_guid":"45F26FDB0CB44852B0ACB5E0165028FD","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"5678BED506A2432AB30DB4800265B549","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"F7914383A4F14441BA24F99CE4D5B8E1","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Perform a single low stringency wash with 6\u00d7 SSC for <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"F20262300CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":600,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"F66E6EE00CF711EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":42,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":600},{"id":1059286,"guid":"313BDD81390B47CFB429207EBD2B4D27","previous_id":1059285,"previous_guid":"63EFC4766DEB4EC7BDDB32E9DD5D3DF7","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"C916F34B6F014331B8581DB0E2909424","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"87231AE5801A482493D38F6CE967CCD7","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Perform a single high stringency wash with <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">preheated <\/span><span>2\u00d7 SSC 0.1% SDS at <\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> for <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">. <\/div><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"07EBF8E00CF811EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":42,"unit":"\u00b0C","title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"0B2356200CF811EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":600,"title":""}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":600},{"id":1059287,"guid":"84CB869354434529B4BA317EEA452E54","previous_id":1059286,"previous_guid":"313BDD81390B47CFB429207EBD2B4D27","modified_on":0,"protocol_id":0,"components":[{"id":1054723,"guid":"0E8C8E6CEA58437B97D0CF3E8314DDCE","order_id":1,"type_id":6,"title":"Section","source":{"title":"Hybridization of DNA Oligonucleotide Probes"}},{"id":1054724,"guid":"6493FC2170DA4A3982770FA05A2B4E70","order_id":1,"type_id":1,"title":"description","source":{"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Perform one last wash for <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> with <\/div><div class = \"text-block\"> at <\/div><div class = \"text-block\">.<\/div><br\/><\/div>"}},{"id":1054725,"guid":"1F5B93500CF811EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":2,"type_id":4,"title":"duration","source":{"duration":600,"title":""}},{"id":1054726,"guid":"3221F1000CF811EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":3,"type_id":3,"title":"amount","source":{"amount":50,"unit":"mL","title":"6\u00d7 SSC "}},{"id":1054727,"guid":"3B0184700CF811EB902293CDC15792DA","order_id":4,"type_id":24,"title":"temperature","source":{"temperature":0,"unit":"Room temperature","title":""}},{"id":1054728,"guid":"95BA82705C154AF0B69DF708E5542643","order_id":5,"type_id":26,"title":"notes","source":{"id":0,"parent_id":0,"uri":"","title":"","body":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Washing twice for 30\u00a0min each with 2\u00d7 SSC 0.5% SDS at 42\u00a0\u00b0C can improve signal-to-noise but can also reduce the signal for some probes. The easiest approach when using a new probe is to follow the low stringency washing protocol, expose the membrane and if background is unacceptable rewash using these more stringent conditions.<\/div><\/div>","created_on":0,"changed_on":0,"creator":{"name":"","affiliation":null,"affiliations":[],"username":"","note":null,"link":null,"image":{"source":"","placeholder":""},"badges":[],"verified":0,"is_verified_user":false,"research_interests":null,"blocked_by_you":false,"blocked_you":false,"hide_following":false},"comments":[]}}],"cases":[],"data":null,"html":null,"section":null,"section_color":"#A492FF","section_duration":10200,"critical":null,"critical_id":null,"duration":600}],"document":"","materials":[],"description":"<div class = \"text-blocks\"><div class = \"text-block\">Over the past decade a plethora of noncoding RNAs (ncRNAs) have been identified, initiating an explosion in RNA research. Although RNA sequencing methods provide unsurpassed insights into ncRNA distribution and expression, detailed information on structure and processing are harder to extract from sequence data. In contrast, northern blotting methods provide uniquely detailed insights into complex RNA populations but are rarely employed outside specialist RNA research groups. Such techniques are generally considered difficult for nonspecialists, which is unfortunate as substantial technical advances in the past few decades have solved the major challenges. Here we present simple, reproducible and highly robust protocols for separating glyoxylated RNA on agarose gels and heat denatured RNA on polyacrylamide\u2013urea gels using standard laboratory electrophoresis equipment. We also provide reliable transfer and hybridization protocols that do not require optimization for most applications. Together, these should allow any molecular biology lab to elucidate the structure and processing of ncRNAs of interest.<\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\"><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Introduction<\/span><\/div><br\/><div class = \"text-block\">Northern blotting methods allow for simultaneous quantification and molecular weight determination of RNA. Although superseded by qPCR and sequencing methods for routine mRNA quantification, northern blotting is the method of choice when complex mixtures of overlapping species are under investigation. This is particularly true when studying RNA processing by complexes such as the exosome, and generally aids in resolving the behavior of differentially expressed RNA isoforms. Historically, northern analysis has been something of a black art; running a high-quality formaldehyde gel required substantial skill and a little luck, while radioactive probing of RNA membranes often resulted in terrible cross-hybridization and invisible signals. Fortunately, technology has moved on such that modern northern analysis methods are simple and robust.<\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Electrophoretic separation of single-stranded RNA is more complex than double-stranded DNA as RNA forms strong secondary structures that impede separation by molecular weight in a gel matrix. For analysis of high molecular weight RNA in agarose gels, chemical modification of guanine is the preferred method to melt secondary structure, which disrupts C:G base pairing and allows single stranded RNA to migrate according to size. Although formaldehyde has been widely used for this purpose [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR1\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">1<\/span><\/a><span>], it is not ideal due to issues with sample migration and batch-to-batch variation. Furthermore formaldehyde gels release toxic formaldehyde gas; this did not overly concern early investigators eager to replace the hideously toxic denaturant methyl mercury used in the first northern blotting protocols [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR2\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">2<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR3\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">3<\/span><\/a><span>], but is clearly a problem in modern labs. To circumvent these issues glyoxal was long ago suggested as an effective RNA denaturant [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR4\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">4<\/span><\/a><span>], but originally required technically awkward buffer recirculation. This problem was solved by the introduction of BPTE running buffer, which allows agarose gels of glyoxylated RNA to be run with no more difficulty than a normal DNA agarose gel [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR5\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">5<\/span><\/a><span>].<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>High-resolution separation of small RNA fragments (~20\u2013250\u00a0bp) is best performed on denaturing acrylamide gels, which rely on heat and urea rather than chemical modification to prevent secondary structure formation. The technique is identical to traditional sequencing gel electrophoresis [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR6\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">6<\/span><\/a><span>], however, the apparatus used for sequencing is not practical for northern blotting and standard protein gel electrophoresis systems are well-suited for this purpose. Helpfully, many of the complications inherent to running a high quality sequencing gel can be safely ignored unless base-pair resolution is required.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>Separated RNA is transferred to a membrane by capillary transfer for agarose gels or using an electroblotting system for acrylamide gels [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR7\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">7<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR8\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">8<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR9\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">9<\/span><\/a><span>]. Various different membranes and transfer conditions have been described but we find charged nylon membrane best for all standard applications [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR10\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">10<\/span><\/a><span>], and observe little difference between transfer methods. Similarly, many combinations of probes and hybridization buffers can be used to detect RNA species, each having their own strengths and weaknesses. Here we provide a protocol for using RNA probes transcribed from PCR products; in our hands these are both the most reliable and the most sensitive, and as such are the probe of choice for new users [<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR11\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">11<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR12\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">12<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR13\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">13<\/span><\/a><span style = \":;:;:UNDERLINE;:UNDERLINE;\">,<\/span><a href=\"https:\/\/link.springer.com\/protocol\/10.1007\/978-1-4939-9822-7_5#CR14\" style = \"text-decoration:underline;color:blue;cursor:pointer;\"><span style = \":;:UNDERLINE;\">14<\/span><\/a><span>]. We also provide probing conditions for use of synthetic oligonucleotides, which are widely used in RNA processing analysis since they provide unparalleled resolution of intermediates, and for random-primed DNA probes.<\/span><\/div><div class = \"text-block\"><span>The source of RNA used for northern blotting is rarely critical as long as it is of high quality (<\/span><span style = \"font-style:italic;\">see <\/span><span style = \"font-weight:bold;\">Note 1<\/span><span>), and therefore in this chapter we focus purely on the gel systems and hybridization methods.<\/span><\/div><\/div>","changed_on":1630617620}